vior. Writing unit tests first often leads to testing mocks rather than real behavior.\\n\\n- **Concrete E2E tier progression.** Steps 4-13 in `implementer.md` lay out a clear progression from simplest test (`TestHumanOnlyChangesAndCommits` ŌĆö no agent prompts needed) to complex scenarios (`TestSubagentCommitFlow`). This is well thought out.\\n\\n- **Research outputs a one-pager instead of a report.** The `AGENT.md` one-pager in the agent package directory is better than a free-form report ŌĆö it persists as development documentation and has a structured template that phases 2-3 can reference.\\n\\n- **Clearer parameter table.** The new SKILL.md parameter table distinguishes between `AGENT_PACKAGE` (Go package, no hyphens), `AGENT_KEY` (registry key), and `AGENT_SLUG` (kebab-case for filesystem) ŌĆö important distinctions that were previously conflated.\\n\\n- **Scope clarification.** Explicitly scoping to hook-capable agents (implementing `HookSupport`) and pointing to `agent.go` for interface definitions.\\n\\n- **Commit checkpoints between phases.** Each phase/step now ends with a `/commit` reminder, which prevents losing work during long multi-phase runs.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issues\\n\\n**Typo:**\\n- `implement.md` line 8: `\\\"E2E-first Test driven develpoment\\\"` ŌĆö \\\"develpoment\\\" should be \\\"development\\\"\\n\\n**Researcher is now too restricted:**\\n- `researcher.md` adds `\\\"**Do NOT read other internal Entire source files** beyond agent-guide.md\\\"`. This seems overly restrictive. The researcher's job is to understand compatibility, and skimming `event.go` (to see actual EventType constants) or `agent.go` (to see the interface) would help produce a more accurate hook-to-EventType mapping table. The agent-guide.md may not always be perfectly in sync with the source. Consider softening to \\\"prefer agent-guide.md, but may reference event.go/agent.go for exact names.\\\"\\n\\n**Step 6 in implementer.md has inconsistent lint-only instruction:**\\n- The \\\"Core Principle\\\" section says `\\\"No unit tests during Steps 4-13\\\"` and `\\\"Format and lint, don't unit test\\\"`, but Step 3 says `\\\"mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test\\\"`. The distinction is explained as \\\"compile-only sanity check\\\" but `mise run test` runs actual tests, not just compilation. If you truly want compile-only, use `go build ./...` instead. This could confuse agents into running the full test suite between every E2E tier.\\n\\n**E2E flakiness guidance could be stronger:**\\n- Step 13 acknowledges flakiness (`\\\"E2E tests can be flaky when run all at once\\\"`) but the mitigation is just \\\"re-run individually.\\\" Consider documenting known flakiness patterns or whether there's a sequential-only flag.\\n\\n**Missing rollback guidance:**\\n- The old doc had guidance on what to do if a step produces bad code. The new doc focuses on the happy path (run, fail, fix, repeat) but doesn't address what happens if an implementation for Tier N breaks a previously-passing Tier M. Adding a note like \\\"if a passing tier regresses, fix the regression before advancing\\\" would help.\\n\\n**Test-writer phase lost useful content:**\\n- The old `test-writer.md` had a full example of how to write agent-specific test scenarios (the `TestAgentSpecificBehavior` example with `ForEachAgent`, `t.Skip`, etc.). While the new philosophy says \\\"no new test scenarios,\\\" this pattern is still useful for agents with genuinely unique behaviors. Consider keeping it as an appendix or \\\"escape hatch\\\" section.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Minor Suggestions\\n\\n- **implementer.md Step 14 (unit tests):** The instruction to use \\\"real data from E2E runs as golden fixtures\\\" is good but could benefit from a concrete example of how to extract that data (e.g., \\\"copy JSON payloads from `e2e/artifacts/{timestamp}/captures/` into `testdata/` directory\\\").\\n\\n- **SKILL.md parameter table:** The `AGENT_KEY` description says to check `cmd/entire/cli/